1) Explain why something you do every day is secretly extremely complex

Action: Catching a ball

Looks simple: see ball → move hand → catch.

What’s actually happening:

* Your brain is solving a real-time physics problem without equations
* It’s predicting a parabolic trajectory based on incomplete visual data
* It’s correcting for:
    * air resistance
    * spin
    * your own body movement
* Your eyes are sampling frames → your brain is interpolating motion between them
* Your muscles are firing in millisecond-timed sequences
* Feedback loops are constantly updating mid-flight

You’re basically running:

continuous prediction + error correction + motor execution

No conscious math. No interface. No lag.

It feels like instinct.
It’s actually embedded computation—hardware-level intelligence.

